          why: "The foundation of reliable database applications. Understanding isolation levels is critical for avoiding bugs in concurrent systems.",
          how: "Isolation levels (weakest to strongest): Read Uncommitted (dirty reads), Read Committed (no dirty reads, default in PostgreSQL/Oracle), Repeatable Read (no non-repeatable reads, default MySQL InnoDB), Serializable (no phantom reads, full isolation). Higher isolation = more locking = less concurrency.",
          tradeoffs: "Serializable is safest but kills throughput. Read Committed is the practical default. Phantom reads (a range query returns different rows in same transaction) require Serializable or SELECT FOR UPDATE. Distributed ACID (across services) requires 2PC or Sagas.",
          interview: "Must know isolation anomalies: Dirty read (read uncommitted data), Non-repeatable read (same row different value in same txn), Phantom read (same range query different rows). 'Which level prevents phantom reads?' → Serializable (or Repeatable Read in MySQL due to gap locks). PostgreSQL SSI: Serializable Snapshot Isolation avoids most locks.",
          example: "Stripe payment processing: Serializable isolation prevents double-charging — two concurrent requests to charge the same invoice both read balance=100, only one can commit (SSI detects the write-write conflict). Bank transfer: BEGIN → debit account A → credit account B → COMMIT (atomic, consistent, isolated, durable).",
