          what: "Little's Law: L = λW. L = average number of items in system. λ = average arrival rate. W = average time per item. Applies to any stable queuing system.",
          why: "Fundamental for capacity planning. Relates the three key metrics: concurrency, throughput, latency. If you know two, you can derive the third.",
          how: "Example: 100 RPS (λ), average 50ms latency (W) → L = 100 × 0.05 = 5 concurrent requests. To double throughput to 200 RPS without increasing latency: need 10 concurrent handlers. To reduce latency from 50ms to 25ms at same 100 RPS: need 2.5 concurrent handlers.",
          tradeoffs: "Assumes stable system (arrival rate = departure rate). Doesn't account for variance. Queueing theory (M/M/c) extends this for variable arrival rates and service times.",
